This is cool and a much needed fix. I was poking around with a similar fix on my local version Friday. One thing I noticed is that column names seem to be downcast somewhere between the query and the viz. If that was changed, this step wouldn't be necessary. If you print the `self.columns` in the `/connectors/sqla/models.py` file in the `get_sqla_query()` method, the column names are all upper. but when it ends up in the `/viz.py` file they're downcast. I'm still not sure where that's happening, but it makes me think a better solution might be somewhere else.
@TryHarder01  Figuring out *precisely* where it happens may be  helpful. I can see that the patch works for you but looks to me it's done in the wrong place.

@xrmx agree on solving it in the right spot. 

I might have a PR ready this afternoon in a different spot.

Adding more context on what I've found out. Oracle DBs / SQLAlch will return a lower case column EXCEPT if the column has mixed case. under the hood Superset renames the "min" , "max", etc.... metrics calls by querying the data and renaming the columns `min(XXXX) as min__XXXX` I traced this all the way up to the `models.core.Database.get_df()` One idea I've thought about is all the calculated metrics could also be in all caps. For example, `min(x) as MIN__X` and then we could have `.upper()` to make sure everything is upper. Right now, we'll need to apply something to make sure these calc'd metrics aren't made upper and that any future metrics don't become upper, but yet we also catch the names of any other columns from the database. This seems like a dangerous tightrope to walk.
